</h3><h3 tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kHOZwM hRBLBR pf-103_">Bolam v Friern Hospital Management Committee (1957)
</h3><p class="sc-hOGkXu hVdrsp pf-105_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The Bolam v Friern Hospital Management Committee (1957) case significantly impacted medical negligence law in the UK by introducing the "Bolam Test." This legal standard assesses a healthcare professional's conduct against the practices accepted as proper by a responsible body of medical opinion at the time. The case arose from John Bolam's injury during electroconvulsive therapy, leading to a ruling that highlighted the latitude in professional judgment. A healthcare provider isn't considered negligent if their actions align with practices endorsed by many esteemed peers, even if there's a contrary opinion. This principle underlines the crucial role of peer-reviewed standards in medical practice, shaping how clinical negligence is evaluated to this day.
</p><h3 tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kHOZwM hRBLBR pf-107_">Montgomery v Lanarkshire Health Board (2015)
</h3><p class="sc-hOGkXu hVdrsp pf-109_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The Montgomery v Lanarkshire Health Board (2015) case fundamentally transformed the UK's legal landscape around informed consent. Nadine Montgomery, a diabetic woman of small stature, gave birth to a son who suffered severe brain damage due to complications during delivery. She argued that she was not informed about the significant risk of shoulder dystocia, nor was she offered a cesarean section as an alternative. The Supreme Court's ruling underscored the duty of healthcare professionals to disclose any and all risks that might affect a patient's decision-making process. This case shifted the focus from a professional to a patient-centred standard, emphasising that patients must be aware of material risks and alternatives, thereby significantly changing the dynamics of doctor-patient communication and consent dynamics.<br><br>These cases have significantly influenced current practices, embedding patient rights and professional responsibilities at the core of clinical observations.
