</h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/5_834dc8bd-8346-4615-99b9-7a6b7e414fc4.png?v=1709733620" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/5_834dc8bd-8346-4615-99b9-7a6b7e414fc4.png?v=1709733620 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/5_834dc8bd-8346-4615-99b9-7a6b7e414fc4_1000x.png?v=1709733620 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/5_834dc8bd-8346-4615-99b9-7a6b7e414fc4_500x.png?v=1709733620 320w" width="1300" height="867" alt="Ensuring Patient Safety Protocols: Best Practices in Clinical Observations - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Ensuring Patient Safety Protocols: Best Practices in Clinical Observations - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-fbyfCU cCdixN pf-231_"/><p class="sc-hOGkXu hVdrsp pf-232_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Image by  DC_Studio via Envato Elements</p><p class="sc-hOGkXu hVdrsp pf-234_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Negligence in clinical observations can lead to misdiagnosis, delayed treatment, and in some cases, irreversible harm. Healthcare professionals are accountable for their actions, with legal implications ranging from professional sanctions to legal proceedings.
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-furwcr dAWGlU pf-236_ pf-r pf-c-cm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fHeRUh cCunWv pf-237_"><h3 tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kHOZwM hRBLBR pf-238_">Case law examples
</h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/7_939b7c1e-c6b0-40c8-a02e-9d7d01579c0d.png?v=1709733619" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/7_939b7c1e-c6b0-40c8-a02e-9d7d01579c0d.png?v=1709733619 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/7_939b7c1e-c6b0-40c8-a02e-9d7d01579c0d_1500x.png?v=1709733619 1280w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/7_939b7c1e-c6b0-40c8-a02e-9d7d01579c0d_1000x.png?v=1709733619 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/7_939b7c1e-c6b0-40c8-a02e-9d7d01579c0d_500x.png?v=1709733619 320w" width="1664" height="2496" alt="Mastering Healthcare Compliance Standards: A Guide for Clinical Observers - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Mastering Healthcare Compliance Standards: A Guide for Clinical Observers - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-fbyfCU cCdixN pf-240_"/><p class="sc-hOGkXu hVdrsp pf-241_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Image by FabrikaPhoto via Envato Ele0ments</p><h3 tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kHOZwM hRBLBR pf-243_">Bolam v Friern Hospital Management Committee (1957)
</h3><p class="sc-hOGkXu hVdrsp pf-245_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The Bolam v Friern Hospital Management Committee (1957) case significantly impacted medical negligence law in the UK by introducing the "Bolam Test." This legal standard assesses a healthcare professional's conduct against the practices accepted as proper by a responsible body of medical opinion at the time. The case arose from John Bolam's injury during electroconvulsive therapy, leading to a ruling that highlighted the latitude in professional judgment. A healthcare provider isn't considered negligent if their actions align with practices endorsed by many esteemed peers, even if there's a contrary opinion. This principle underlines the crucial role of peer-reviewed standards in medical practice, shaping how clinical negligence is evaluated to this day.
</p><h3 tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kHOZwM hRBLBR pf-247_">Montgomery v Lanarkshire Health Board (2015)
</h3><p class="sc-hOGkXu hVdrsp pf-249_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The Montgomery v Lanarkshire Health Board (2015) case fundamentally transformed the UK's legal landscape around informed consent. Nadine Montgomery, a diabetic woman of small stature, gave birth to a son who suffered severe brain damage due to complications during delivery. She argued that she was not informed about the significant risk of shoulder dystocia, nor was she offered a cesarean section as an alternative. The Supreme Court's ruling underscored the duty of healthcare professionals to disclose any and all risks that might affect a patient's decision-making process. This case shifted the focus from a professional to a patient-centred standard, emphasising that patients must be aware of material risks and alternatives, thereby significantly changing the dynamics of doctor-patient communication and consent dynamics.<br><br>These cases have significantly influenced current practices, embedding patient rights and professional responsibilities at the core of clinical observations.
